Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The core challenge in learning sentiment-aware topics lies in balancing interpretability, differentiability, and dynamic evolution of topic-word distributions over continuous time. Traditional topic models like LDA or even neural variants such as NVDM or ETM treat topics as static or use non-differentiable sampling (e.g., via reparameterized Gumbel-Softmax), which hinders true end-to-end learning—especially when sentiment modulation is involved. Inspired by Papers 1 and 2, I recognize that modeling dynamics through differential equations offers a powerful framework for continuous representation learning. However, existing NODE-based models focus on state transformations in vision or sequence tasks, not on latent topic dynamics conditioned on sentiment. Paper 3 highlights the importance of interpretability and class-specific pattern discovery—here, sentiment classes (positive/negative/neutral) can be seen as drivers of differential topic expression. My key insight is to model topic-word distributions as evolving continuous processes governed by *sentiment-conditioned neural differential equations*, where the derivative of the topic distribution is learned via a neural operator that responds dynamically to sentiment cues. This enables both differentiable sampling and interpretable, sentiment-driven topic drift. Unlike prior work, this approach unifies continuous-time topic evolution, differentiable word distribution sampling, and explicit sentiment conditioning within a single end-to-end trainable framework. It also introduces piecewise-constant sentiment influence zones (inspired by Paper 2’s PCDDEs), allowing topics to evolve differently during sustained sentiment states—critical for real-world text with shifting emotional tones.

