Idea 0 introduces a NODE-based continuous-time evolution of topic-word distributions modulated by sentiment, with a novel "flow-through softmax" and extension to piecewise-constant delay differential equations (PCDDEs) inspired by Paper 2. While Paper 2 discusses neural dynamic models with Bernoulli processes for topic activity and mentions PCDDEs in passing (via the name), it does not employ differential equations over simplex-valued topic distributions or enable end-to-end differentiable training via ODE solvers. The use of NODEs for modeling continuous topic flows conditioned on sentiment is not present in any of the provided papers. Moreover, the integration of spectral operators (inspired by BFNO from Paper 1) into topic modeling—though Paper 1 focuses on scalable collapsed inference using Monte Carlo methods in discrete LDA-style models—is a significant departure, making this component orthogonal rather than overlapping.

Idea 1 goes further by introducing stochastic differential equations (SDEs) on hyperbolic manifolds, incorporating uncertainty quantification via SDE path sampling, and using Poincaré embeddings for hierarchical topic structure. While Papers 4 and 5 explore uncertainty quantification in NLP (Bayesian summarization and UQ in LLMs), they do so without modeling topic dynamics or geometric representations. The use of SDEs on manifolds for topic evolution has no direct counterpart in the listed papers. Furthermore, the combination of hyperbolic geometry, stochastic dynamics, sentiment-modulated drift-diffusion switching, and manifold-constrained reparameterization represents a unique synthesis that is not addressed in prior work.

However, upon close inspection, Idea 1 integrates *more distinct innovations*—geometric representation (hyperbolic space), stochastic dynamics (SDEs), uncertainty-aware sampling, multi-scale sentiment gating, and manifold-preserving gradients—into a unified framework that none of the existing papers touch upon. Paper 4 uses Bayesian methods for uncertainty but in summarization; Paper 5 shifts attention for UQ in LLMs but doesn't model latent semantic trajectories. There is no prior work combining differential geometry with stochastic topic dynamics conditioned on sentiment.

While both ideas are novel, **Idea 1** pushes further beyond the current frontier by unifying uncertainty quantification, non-Euclidean geometry, and continuous-time stochastic dynamics in a differentiable topic modeling framework—a combination not seen in the provided literature or commonly in the field. It addresses not just interpretability and end-to-end learning but also *calibrated uncertainty*, which is critical for real-world deployment and underexplored in topic modeling. Therefore, despite higher complexity, its conceptual and technical leap justifies higher novelty.

